value.0: Black Dragons are evil-tempered, cunning, and malevolent. Especially fond of coins, they often question their humanoid prey about stockpiles of gold before killing them.
Blue Dragons are vain and territorial. They prefer to hunt on cloudless days, when their blue scales allow them to blend with the open skies.
Green Dragons are belligerent and prone to attacking without provocation. They make their lairs in old growth forests where they fly beneath the canopy.
Among the smallest and least intelligent of Dragonkind, most White Dragons are simply animalistic predators with a predilection for gems and frozen meat.
Shadow dragons prefer to attack from hiding, employing their natural abilities to blend into the shadows.

The animated bones of an indeterminate variety of dragon, necromantic energies emanate off of this corrupted creature's bones and a deal of malevolent power flickers inside its skull. Despite the frail impression a skeletal creature would have, this corpse no doubt is a fearsome opponent should you cross its master.
Brass Dragons are talkative gossipmongers. They may have useful information, but usually share it only after long rambling and hinting for a gift.
Bronze Dragons are inquisitive and enjoy polymorphing into animals to better observe adventurers. Fascinated by warfare, they'll eagerly join a just cause... for good pay.
Copper Dragons are incorrigible pranksters, joke tellers, and riddlers. Most are good-natured but also have a covetous, miserly streak.
Gold Dragons are graceful, sinuous, and wise. They hate injustice and foul play, often embarking on self-appointed quests to promote good.

Marikus the Red always envied those wizards who specialized in acane duels. In an effort to enhance his performance in such combats Marikus created these slippers. 
It may be noted his dying word were "Fear my fuzzy slippers!" Marikus would have been well served to study his opponents and not rely so heavily in items for his arcane survival.

Celestial, abyssal and infernal runes line each digit of these jet black gloves, and it doesn't take long to reveal that these are no mere decorations - performing certain hand gestures will light up each rune of a certain language in turn, and when all runes of the same language are glowing brightly, a creature of the matching kind will be pulled from its home to do the wearer's bidding. While they've since lost their name, they were a common sight on a Red Wizard who had a flair for the dramatic, regularly summoning servants to assist in studies via complicated, impressive displays of the theatrical. It was said each rune had a small enchantment to store memories, and with the sheer amount of runes on these gloves, they promise to impart a large collection of knowledge upon any who wears them.

This slick, matte, blue-gray leather cloak allows its wearer to stay alive underwater.
Set into a copper band is a single green eye, constantly scanning the area and blinking now and then.  When the eye spots something, a faint tingle can be felt in the ring finger.
A sturdy girdle usually donned by soldiers running grueling training courses. The belt seems to strengthen the body and allow one to pass almost any physical trial.
Belts are worn about the midsection, but do not add to the protection given by basic armor unless infused with magic.

Fiercely sought after by certain trackers and wardens, these helms possess horn-shaped ear cones that amplify the wearer's hearing tenfold. While the materials used in creation offer little in terms of protection to the face, it offers an unrivaled advantage when it comes to aural detection.

A favorite amongst duelists and corsairs alike. This splinted chest plate is made of fine quality Ironwood. Lightweight and sturdy, this armor allows for greater freedom of movement of the wearer whilst also providing protection from various forms of attack.

A tall walking stick made from a yew branch that radiates arcane magic with a rustic twist. Those who revere nature will find that this staff better allows them to tune into their ability to handle wildlife. Additionally, this staff imparts an amount of clarity on the bearer that better allows them to focus on their spells.

Ideal for defending the decks from the crow's nest during a boarding battle, copies of crossbows like this are highly sought-after by sailors, privateers, and pirates alike. Exquisitely crafted, this crossbow bears the remarkable enchantment of a replenishing bolt-holder. Once a bolt is fired from it, another magically appears at the holster on the end.

Runes skillfully carved from the nacre of a seashell decorate this otherwise simple ironwood band, and faintly shift in color without the aid of light, no doubt magical in nature. Notable of the design is a pair of crossed tridents at the center of the ring. Clearly powerfully enchanted, this ring imparts the ability to breathe underwater on the wearer, as well as increase their physical prowess.

With an Onyx buckle and black band, this belt is a fashionable, if ominous accessory. The material used in its construction was allegedly a nightshade of sorts. Strange, umbral energies seem to have been infused in the belt itself that enhance the wearer's stealth as well as their focus. However, wearing the belt produces a certain sense of unease that the noble of heart might find overwhelming.

Cutlasses are large, curved, slashing sabers favored by adventurers and sailors alike. By many standards, this particular cutlass appears normal, save for the serrated cutting edge of the blade. upon closer inspection, a keen observer would notice the serrated edge is crafted from the stingers of several wyverns. By some manner of enchantment, residuals of the poison contained within the wyverns' stingers persists and makes for a wicked affliction to the unfortunate foe of the bearer of this blade.

A sturdy, light, and heavily enchanted shield made from ironwood. Seemingly designed with duels in mind, this shield provides additional protection against thrusting attacks as well as enhances the bearer's resilience, reflexes, and mental discipline.

This pendant appears to be made of a hollow crystal bulb in the shape of a teardrop. Carried within is a small amount of water from an unknown source. The crystal tear is held inside a delicate cage of silver filigree. Perhaps disjointedly, the pendant is strung on a worn leather cord, leading one to suspect that the original chain was lost at some point.

When held close to the ear by one bearing the blood of a Rusalka, a very faint somber melody can be heard emanating from the pendant at night.

Tridents are long, three-pronged, polearms favored by adventurers and certain sea-dwellers alike. By many standards, this particular trident appears normal, save for the serrated cutting edges on the prongs. Upon closer inspection, a keen observer would notice the serrated edge is crafted from the stingers of several wyverns. By some manner of enchantment, residuals of the poison contained within the wyverns' stingers persists and makes for a wicked affliction to the unfortunate foe of the bearer of this blade.

This ruby ring feels... Uncomfortable. A sense of disturbing extraplanar influence can be felt simply by holding it. Only those of a certain mindset can wear it without feeling an overwhelming sense of dread.
